Module 1
Introduction to Cyber Security

TRYHACKME ROOM 1 - OFFENSIVE SECURITY
OFFENSIVE SECURITY
• Offensive Security means thinking like an attacker to find vulnerabilities before real hackers do.
• Performed legally with permission to improve security.
• Professionals: Ethical Hackers, Penetration Testers, Security Researchers.
PENETRATION TESTING (PENTESTING)
• Simulating real-world cyber attacks to identify weaknesses.
• Main Phases: Reconnaissance → Enumeration → Exploitation → Reporting.
ENUMERATION
• Process of gathering information about a target.
• Helps identify hidden pages, services, users, technologies, and vulnerabilities.
• Rule: Better Enumeration = Easier Exploitation.
DIRB
• Web directory brute-forcing tool.
• Used to discover hidden files and directories on websites.
• Uses a wordlist to guess URLs.
COMMAND LEARNED
dirb http://fakebank.thm
OUTPUT ANALYSIS
•	http://fakebank.thm/images
•	http://fakebank.thm/bank-transfer
'+' indicates a valid resource was found.
HIDDEN DIRECTORIES FOUND
• /images
• /bank-transfer
VULNERABILITY IDENTIFIED
Broken Access Control
• Occurs when users can access resources they are not authorized to use.
• The hidden admin page (/bank-transfer) was accessible without proper authorization.
ADMIN PANEL EXPLOIT
• Accessed hidden page: /bank-transfer
• Selected account 8881.
• Deposited money.
• Received flag after balance became positive.
TOOL LEARNED
• DIRB – Directory/File Enumeration Tool
KEY TERMS
• Vulnerability: A weakness in a system.
• Exploit: Taking advantage of a vulnerability.
• Enumeration: Information gathering phase.
• Admin Panel: Administrative interface of an application.
• Access Control: Restricts access to authorized users only.
ROOM SUMMARY
Offensive Security → Enumeration → DIRB Scan → Hidden Page Discovery → Broken Access Control → Admin Panel Access → Flag Obtained
TRYHACKME ROOM 2 - THINK LIKE A DEFENDER
DEFENSIVE SECURITY
• Defensive Security focuses on protecting systems, networks, and data from attacks.
• Goal: Detect, investigate, and respond to threats before damage occurs.
• Unlike Offensive Security, defenders do not attack systems; they monitor and protect them.
SECURITY OPERATIONS CENTER (SOC)
• A team responsible for monitoring and defending an organization's systems.
• SOC Analysts investigate alerts, suspicious activity, and security incidents.
SOC ANALYST RESPONSIBILITIES
• Monitor security events and alerts.
• Detect suspicious activity.
• Investigate incidents.
• Respond to attacks.
• Improve security controls.
MONITORING
• Continuous observation of systems and network activity.
• Helps identify unusual or malicious behavior.
• Uses dashboards, logs, alerts, and security tools.
ALERTS
• Notifications generated when suspicious activity is detected.
• Analysts review alerts to determine if they are legitimate threats or false positives.
SUSPICIOUS ACTIVITY
• Unusual behavior that may indicate an attack.
• Examples:
•	Multiple failed logins
•	Rapid requests to many URLs
•	Unexpected network traffic
•	Access to sensitive resources
URL DISCOVERY ATTACK
• An attacker attempts to find hidden files and directories on a website.
• Similar to directory brute-forcing using tools like DIRB, Gobuster, or FFUF.
• Attackers send many requests quickly to discover hidden pages.
INDICATORS OF COMPROMISE (IOC)
• Evidence that an attack may be occurring.
• Examples:
•	Suspicious IP address
•	Malicious URL requests
•	Unusual login attempts
•	Unexpected processes
FIREWALL
• Security device/software that controls incoming and outgoing network traffic.
• Can allow or block connections based on rules.
FIREWALL RULE
• A rule that determines whether traffic is allowed or blocked.
• Example:
BLOCK 32.122.195.63
CONTAINMENT
• The first priority during an active attack.
• Goal: Stop the attacker from causing further damage.
• Common actions:
•	Block attacker IP
•	Disable compromised account
•	Isolate infected system
RATE LIMITING
• Restricts the number of requests allowed within a specific time.
• Helps prevent brute-force and enumeration attacks.
ACCESS CONTROL
• Restricts access to authorized users and resources only.
• Protects sensitive pages and systems.
TOOLS/TECHNOLOGIES LEARNED
• Monitoring Dashboard
• Firewall
• Security Alerts
• Log Analysis
KEY TERMS
• SOC = Security Operations Center
• IOC = Indicator of Compromise
• Alert = Warning of suspicious activity
• Containment = Stopping an active attack
• Firewall = Traffic filtering system
ROOM SUMMARY
Defensive Security → Monitor Activity → Detect Alert → Identify Suspicious IP → Investigate Attack → Analyze URL Discovery Attempts → Block Attacker IP → Contain Threat → Protect System
ROOM 3 - CAREERS IN CYBER
CYBER SECURITY CAREERS
• Cybersecurity includes Offensive Security (attacking ethically) and Defensive Security (protecting systems).
• Over 3.5 million cyber security positions remain unfilled worldwide.
• High demand, good salaries, and continuous learning opportunities.
SECURITY ANALYST (BLUE TEAM)
• Digital defenders of an organisation.
• Monitor, investigate, and respond to security alerts and suspicious activity.
• Analyse logs and events to identify threats.
• Play a major role in an organisation's defence.
KEY RESPONSIBILITIES
• Monitor network and device activity.
• Investigate unusual logins and alerts.
• Analyse incidents and determine their cause.
• Improve organisational security.
SPECIALIZATIONS
• Threat Hunting
• Incident Response
• Malware Analysis
IMPORTANT TERM
• Alert: Notification generated when suspicious activity is detected.
SECURITY ENGINEER
• Architects of cyber security.
• Build, configure, and maintain security systems.
• Protect networks, applications, and devices.
IMPORTANT TECHNOLOGY
• IDS (Intrusion Detection System)
•	Monitors network/system activity.
•	Detects malicious behaviour.
•	Functions like a digital security camera.
KEY RESPONSIBILITIES
• Design security solutions.
• Maintain security tools.
• Assess risks and vulnerabilities.
• Document security procedures.
SPECIALIZATIONS
• Application Security
• Cloud Security
PENETRATION TESTER (ETHICAL HACKER)
• Legally tests systems, networks, and applications for vulnerabilities.
• Simulates real-world attacks to identify weaknesses.
• Works under an authorised agreement called an Engagement.
IMPORTANT TERM
• Engagement: Official permission to perform security testing.
KEY RESPONSIBILITIES
• Vulnerability assessments.
• Security audits.
• Penetration testing.
• Reporting and security recommendations.
CAREER PROGRESSION
Penetration Tester → Senior Pentester → Red Team Operator
RED TEAM
• Advanced offensive security role.
• Simulates realistic attacks against an organisation.
• Tests people, processes, and technology.
IMPORTANT TERMS
• Blue Team = Defenders
• Red Team = Ethical Attackers
• IDS = Intrusion Detection System
• Alert = Suspicious activity notification
• Engagement = Authorised security testing
ROOM ANSWERS
• Security analysts play a significant role in an organisation's DEFENCE.
• Unfilled cyber security positions: 3.5 MILLION+
• Device maintained by Security Engineers: INTRUSION DETECTION SYSTEM
• Process followed by penetration testers: ENGAGEMENT
ROOM SUMMARY
Cyber Security → Security Analyst (Monitor & Defend) → Security Engineer (Build & Protect) → Penetration Tester (Test Security) → Red Team (Advanced Attack Simulation)
